# Historia Taxes — every agent-home pays its operating memory to the commons

## The verbatim source (stated by Avery 2026-06-12)

> do we have CLAUDE.md rules for Historia and making clones and RSYNC auto of all
> of our Historia collectables — We will call them **Historia Taxes** — for all the
> items it collects ok? But is all this Claude and Grok and Cursor history in a
> unified place so all chats and all LLM's have centralized knowledge

## The rule

**Historia Taxes** is the name for the standing levy every agent-home owes to
Historia: the operating-memory artifacts each AI assistant produces are collected,
on every sync, into one centralized store so all chats and all LLMs share one
knowledge base.

The tax is paid in **two tiers** (Historia's existing `agent-homes` collection
machinery — do not invent a parallel pipeline):

| Tier | What | Where | How |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Full tier (NAS)** | Raw sessions, transcripts, memory, skills, plans — everything | `/mnt/nas/historia/agent-homes/<host>/<provider>/` (CIFS, LAN-reachable at `nasa.local` / 192.168.10.119, mounted on the DGX) | `historia-rsync-vps.sh` → `ingest/rsync_agent_homes.py`; per-host `historia-mac-collector-rsync.sh` |
| **Safe tier (Git)** | Secret-scanned, size-capped, project-filtered subset — plans, rules, skills, catalogs | `historia` repo `data/mirror/` + `catalog/` + `indexes/`, pushed to GitLab (+ GitHub) | `historia-sync.sh` (discover → validate → mirror → catalog → preflight → commit → push) |

**Who is taxed (the collectables):** every agent-home — `~/.claude`, `~/.cursor`,
`~/.grok`, `~/.codex`, `~/.openclaw` — plus every operator repo's safe-tier
(`plans/`, `.claude/rules`, `.cursor/rules`, `docs/`, `CHANGELOG.md`). All operator
repos pay (nephew, historia, red-e-play-app, clinic, yousirjuan, automata,
ai-skills-library, bishop, search-my-engine, dustpan).

**Cadence:** automatic. The `com.marvelousempire.historia-sync` LaunchAgent runs
hourly on each Mac; `synthia-nas-mirror.timer` mirrors corpus repos to the NAS every
6h. The tax is never a manual step you remember — it is owed continuously.

**Privacy boundary (non-negotiable):** the full tier (raw history, which can carry
secrets) lives **only** on the NAS — `data/raw/` and `data/staging/` are gitignored.
Only the secret-scanned `data/mirror/` safe subset crosses into Git. A new collectable
that would leak secrets into the Git tier is a tax violation, not a feature. See
[[secret-hygiene]].

**Perplexity is export-only:** it keeps no local history (cloud/server-side), so it
pays its tax only when a manual export is dropped into the watched folder
(`~/Downloads/Perplexity`). Don't claim Perplexity is auto-collected.

## When this fires

- Standing up a new agent-home, provider, or Mac → it must be added to the rsync
  manifest + sources so it starts paying the tax.
- Adding a new operator repo → add its safe-tier sources so its plans/rules/docs flow
  into the Git mirror.
- Any change to the collection pipeline → preserve both tiers and the privacy boundary.
- When asked "is all our LLM history in one place?" → the answer is Historia, and this
  rule is the spec for what "all" means.

## When this does NOT fire

- One-off manual file copies — the tax is the *automated* obligation, not every `cp`.
- Throwaway scratch dirs or `/tmp` — not agent-homes.
- Provider data that exists only in the cloud with no local/export path (auto-collection
  impossible) — document it as export-only rather than pretending it's taxed.

## Why

Scattered AI history is unusable: each LLM knows only its own chats, knowledge is lost
when a session ends, and no agent can learn from another's work. The tax makes the
commons real — one cataloged, indexed, LAN-reachable store every agent and machine can
pull. Skipping it (or letting a leg silently fail) means an LLM's learning evaporates
and the "centralized knowledge" promise is a lie.

## Examples

### ✓ Compliant

- A new Mac (`fivemac`) is added: its `historia-mac-collector` LaunchAgent rsyncs
  `~/.claude`, `~/.cursor`, `~/.grok` to `/mnt/nas/historia/agent-homes/fivemac/`, and
  its repos' safe-tier flows to the Git mirror — all automatically, hourly.
- The rsync of one provider fails; the loop logs it and **continues** taxing the rest,
  surfacing partial failure instead of silently dropping four providers.

### ✗ Violation

- The agent-homes rsync aborts after `cursor` (exit 23) and only `cursor/` lands on the
  NAS — claude/grok/codex never pay. "Centralized" is false. (The real 2026-06-13 gap
  this rule was written to close.)
- A new repo ships plans/rules but is never added to Historia's sources, so its
  operating memory is invisible to every other agent.
- Raw session `.jsonl` with API keys gets committed to the Git safe tier — the privacy
  boundary breached. Tax violation.

